3.6 Estimation
Unlike ordinary least squares, GLMs are usually estimated by maximum likelihood, often using iteratively reweighted least squares (IRLS).
The details of the algorithm are usually less important than the modeling idea:

choose a suitable distribution;
choose a suitable link function;
interpret the fitted model on the correct scale.

4.3 Relation to Linear Regression and GLMs
The progression is:

Linear regression: linear mean function with Gaussian errors;
GLM: linear predictor with a general response distribution and link function;
GAM: additive smooth functions with a general response distribution and link function.

So a GAM is best viewed as a flexible extension of a GLM.

4.7 Relation to Ridge and LASSO
GAMs already use regularization through smoothness penalties. This is a different kind of regularization from ridge regression and LASSO:

ridge shrinks coefficients with an \(L_2\) penalty;
LASSO shrinks coefficients with an \(L_1\) penalty and can set some exactly to zero;
GAMs penalize the roughness of smooth functions.

There are also sparse versions of GAMs that combine smooth modeling with variable selection.

5.8 Summary
The main ideas of ridge regression are:

it adds an \(L_2\) penalty to least squares;
it shrinks coefficients toward zero;
it reduces variance and can improve prediction;
it is particularly useful when predictors are highly correlated;
it usually keeps all variables in the model.

6.2 Why LASSO Is Useful
Ordinary least squares can become unstable when there are many predictors or when predictors are highly correlated. LASSO addresses this by introducing bias in exchange for lower variance and a simpler model.
This can improve prediction, especially when:

only a subset of predictors is truly important;
interpretability matters;
the number of predictors is moderately large.

6.10 Summary
The main ideas of LASSO are:

it adds an \(L_1\) penalty to least squares;
it shrinks coefficients toward zero;
it can set some coefficients exactly to zero;
it is useful for both prediction and variable selection;
the tuning parameter \(\lambda\) is usually chosen by cross-validation.
